<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1890-06-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1890-06-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="139" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d139">
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Denby</persName></hi>.</head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1890-06-27"><hi rend="italic">June</hi> 27,
                            1890</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 544.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your No. 1114 of the 10th
                        ultimo, in relation to a note from the yamên of the previous day, on the
                        subject of “the fixation of the duration of export transit passes.”</p>
                    <p>The suggestion in Mr. von Brandt’s <hi rend="italic">memorandum</hi>, of
                        which you inclose a copy, that the period of validity of transit passes in
                        the several districts and treaty ports of China be determined by mutual
                        agreement between the authorities and the consular representatives of the
                        treaty powers, appears to be proper and necessary.</p>
                    <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">James G. Blaine.</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>